Problem Statement¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customer’s age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

# Function to plot a histogram and boxplot

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(10, 6), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (15,10))
    kde: whether to show the density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a triangle will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram
    # Print min, max, mean and median value
    print("Min:{:.2f} Max:{:.2f} Mean:{:.2f} Median:{:.2f}".format(
        data[feature].min(),
        data[feature].max(),
        data[feature].mean(),
        data[feature].median()
    ))

# Function to create labeled barplots

def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 2, 6))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 2, 6))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n],
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

# Function to plot a stacked barplot

def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 5, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left", frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

# Function to plot distributions with relation to the target variable

def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of target for target=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
        stat="density",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t target")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Outlier detection and treatment¶

  • While a few variables do have outliers (Income, CCAvg and Mortgage), they appear to be real datapoints and would provide valuable information for the decision tree model.
  • Therefore they will not be modified.

Dropping ID column¶

  • Every value is unique.
  • It does not provide any value in predicting the target variable.
In [39]:
# Dropping ID column
df.drop('ID',axis=1,inplace=True)

Dropping ZIPCode column¶

  • There are 2 options for dealing with the ZIPCode variable:
    1. Merge the dataframe with a dataset that will allow the zipcode to be mapped to information such as States/Cities/Counties. These variables would need to be one-hot encoded which will increase the dimensionality of the model, which may increase predictive power, but also increases complexity and decreasing efficiency of the model.
    2. Drop the ZIPCode column all together.
  • My personal opinon is that option 1 will not add enough predictive power to make up for loss in model effeciency and therefore go for option 2, where model efficiency is maintained while the other variables (such as Income and Education) will contribute enough predictive power to the model.

Model Evaluation Criterion¶

  • Defining a utlility function to collate evaluation metrics (accuracy, recall, precision and f1 score) into a single dataframe.
In [46]:
def model_performance_classification(model,predictors,target):
  """
  To plot evaluation metrics.

  model: Model to evaluate
  predictors: Independent variables
  target: Dependent variable
  """
  # Predicting using the IVs
  pred=model.predict(predictors)

  # Calculating different metrics
  acc=accuracy_score(target,pred)
  recall=recall_score(target,pred)
  precision=precision_score(target,pred)
  f1=f1_score(target,pred)

  # Creating a dataframe of the evaluation metrics
  df_perf=pd.DataFrame(
      {"Accuracy":acc,"Recall":recall,"Precision":precision,"F1":f1},
      index=[0]
  )
  return df_perf
  • Defining a function to plot the confusion matrix
In [47]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(model,predictors,target):
  """
  To plot confusion matrix with percentages.

  model: Model to evaluate
  predictors: Independent variables
  target: Dependent variable
  """
  # Predicting the target values
  y_pred=model.predict(predictors)

  # Creating a confusion matrix
  cm=confusion_matrix(target,y_pred)

  # Creating labels for each cell in the confusion matrix for both count and percentage
  labels=np.asarray(
      [
          ["{0:0.0f}".format(item)+"\n{0:.2%}".format(item/cm.flatten().sum()) for item in cm.flatten()]
      ]
  ).reshape(2,2)

  #Plotting the confusion matrix with labels
  plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
  sns.heatmap(cm,annot=labels,fmt="")
  plt.ylabel("True label")
  plt.xlabel("Predicted label")
  plt.show()

Model Performance Improvement¶

Pre-Pruning:

  • Let's try to improve the model using pre-pruning.
  • This method bounds the hyperparameters to a predefined criteria and does not allow the tree to grow fully which would lead to overfitting.
In [52]:
# Defining the parameters of the tree to iterate over
max_depth_values=np.arange(2,11,2)
max_leaf_nodes_values=np.arange(5,51,5)
min_samples_split_values=np.arange(5,51,5)

# Initialize variable to store the best model and its performance
best_estimator=None
best_score_diff=float('inf')

# Iterate over all combinations of the specified parameter values
for max_depth in max_depth_values:
  for max_leaf_nodes in max_leaf_nodes_values:
    for min_samples_split in min_samples_split_values:

      # Initialize the tree with the current set of parameters
      estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier(
          max_depth=max_depth,
          max_leaf_nodes=max_leaf_nodes,
          min_samples_split=min_samples_split,
          random_state=RS)
      # Fit the model to the training data
      estimator.fit(X_train,y_train)
      #Make predictions on the train and test sets
      y_train_pred=estimator.predict(X_train)
      y_test_pred=estimator.predict(X_test)
      # Calculate the F1 scores for the train and test sets
      train_f1_score=f1_score(y_train,y_train_pred)
      test_f1_score=f1_score(y_test,y_test_pred)
      # Calculate the absolute difference in F1 scores
      score_diff=abs(train_f1_score-test_f1_score)
      # Update the best estimator and best score if the current one has a smaller score difference
      if score_diff<best_score_diff:
        best_estimator=estimator
        best_score_diff=score_diff
# Best parameters
print("Best Estimator: ", best_estimator)

Best Estimator:  DecisionTreeClassifier(max_depth=np.int64(6), max_leaf_nodes=np.int64(25),
                       min_samples_split=np.int64(5), random_state=42)
  • The best parameters are: max_depth=6, max_leaf_nodes=25, minimum_samples_split=5.

Post-Pruning¶

  • Let's try improve the model using post-pruning.
  • This method lets the tree to fully grow, and then subtrees are pruned and replaced by leaf nodes (using cost complexity pruning).
In [57]:
# Creating an instance of the decision tree model
clf=DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=RS)

# Compute the cost complexity pruning path for the model using training data
path=clf.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train,y_train)

# Extracting the array of effective alphas from pruning path
ccp_alphas=abs(path.ccp_alphas)

# Extracting the array of total impurities at each alpha along the pruning path
impurities=path.impurities

# Plotting the total impurities versus effective alphas, excluding the last value (which is the alpha that corresponds with a tree with one node)
fig, ax=plt.subplots(figsize=(10,6))
ax.plot(ccp_alphas[:-1], impurities[:-1], marker='o', drawstyle="steps-post")
ax.set_xlabel("Effective Alpha")
ax.set_ylabel("Total Impurity of Leaves")
ax.set_title("Total Impurity vs Effective Alpha for Training Set")
plt.show()

Observations:¶

  • As the alpha increases (less model complexity), the impurity increases (which is to be expected).
  • There is a sharp increase in impurity as the alpha increases from 0 to approximately 0.001.
  • The impurity increases gradually as alpha approaches approximately 0.004.
  • We will find the optimal alpha next (which will likely be in the range 0.000-0.003) by training a decision tree using the effective alphas.
In [58]:
# Initialize an empty list to store the decision tree classifiers
clfs=[]

# Iterate over each ccp_alpha value extracted from the cost complexity pruning path
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
  # Create an instance of the decision tree classifier
  clf=DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=RS,ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha)
  # Fit the classifier to the training data
  clf.fit(X_train,y_train)
  # Append the classifier to the list
  clfs.append(clf)

# Remove the last classifier and corresponding ccp_alpha value from the lists (as this corresponds to the tree with one node)
clfs=clfs[:-1]
ccp_alphas=ccp_alphas[:-1]

# Initialize an empty list to store F1 scores for each classifier on the test set
test_f1_scores=[]

# Iterate over each classifier in the list
for clf in clfs:
  # Make predictions on the test set using the classifier
  pred_test=clf.predict(X_test)
  # Calculate the F1 score for the predictions
  f1_test=f1_score(y_test,pred_test)
  # Append the F1 score to the list
  test_f1_scores.append(f1_test)

# Creating the model where we get the highest test F1 score
index_best_clf=np.argmax(test_f1_scores)

# Selecting the decision tree model corresponding to the highest test score
dtree3=clfs[index_best_clf]
print(dtree3)

DecisionTreeClassifier(ccp_alpha=np.float64(0.0008702884311333967),
                       random_state=42)

Observations:¶

  • The optimal effective alpha= 0.00087.

Model Comparison:¶

  • Default model:
    • Performance metrics on the train set are perfect (which is expected). This leads to overfitting.
    • Performance metrics on the test set are relatively decent, but it is clear that the model is overfitted as the performance metrics are worse than the train set.
    • It is the most complex tree.
  • Pre-pruned model:
    • The performance metrics on the test set have improved compared to the test set from the default model.
      • Therefore the pre-pruned model performs better and is more robust compared to the default model.
    • The performance metrics in the train and test sets are similar (especially Accuracy and F1 Score).
      • This means that the pre-pruned model has good generalization ability.
    • It is important to note that the test set performed worst on Precision, which in the context of loan approval, is not a good thing as the bank should avoid wrongly approving bad loans.
    • The tree is less complex than the default tree.
  • Post-pruned model:
    • The performance on the test set have the highest metrics across all parameters among the 3 models.
    • Surprsingly, the performance metrics on the test set are better than the train set (except for Precision).
      • Therefore not only did the model genralize well, it performed better on unseen data.
        • This should be investigated further.
    • It is the least complex tree.

Model Selection:¶

  • It is clear that the best model is the Post-pruned Decision Tree:
  1. Performance
  • The post-pruned model performed the best on the test set compared to the rest of the models on Accuracy, Recall, Precision and F1 Score.
  1. Generalization ability
  • The post-pruned model generalized the best on the test set, even performing better than the train set.
  1. Complexity and computational cost
  • While the post-pruning method has a higher computational cost than the pre-pruning method, it lead to the least complex tree (even less complex than the pre-pruned tree).
  • This is because the post-pruning method is more targeted and data-driven than the pre-pruning method. It selectively prunes away subtrees that do not contain much predictive power. This leaves behind a much simpler, yet more powerful predictive model.

Actionable Insights and Business Recommendations¶

Actionable Insights:¶

  • Key Drivers for Personal Loan Purchase:
    • The most significant attributes influencing a customer's likelihood of purchasing a personal loan are Income, Education, Family size, Average Credit Card spending (CCAvg), and whether they have a Certificate of Deposit (CD) account. Other features like Age, Experience, Mortgage, Securities Account, Online banking usage, and Credit Card usage with other banks appear to have little to no impact on this decision according to the model.
  • Income as a Primary Indicator:
    • Income is the most crucial factor in determining if a customer will take a personal loan. Customers with higher incomes are more likely to be interested.
  • Education Level Matters:
    • Customers with higher education levels (Graduate and Advanced/Professional) are more inclined to take personal loans compared to those with an Undergraduate education.
  • Family Size and Spending Habits:
    • Both family size and average credit card spending play a role in predicting loan uptake, suggesting that customers with larger families and those who spend more on credit cards might have different financial needs or behaviors that make them more receptive to personal loans.
  • CD Account Holders are Potential Targets:
    • Customers who already have a CD account are more likely to be open to personal loan offers. This might indicate a segment of customers who are already actively engaged with the bank's financial products.

Business Recommendations:¶

  • Targeted Marketing Campaigns:
    • Focus marketing efforts for personal loans on liability customers who fit the profile of those most likely to purchase based on the key attributes identified:
      • Customers with higher incomes.
      • Customers with Graduate or Advanced/Professional education levels.
      • Customers with specific family sizes and credit card spending patterns (further analysis could be done on specific ranges of these attributes).
      • Customers who hold CD accounts with the bank.
  • Tailored Loan Offers:
    • Develop different personal loan offers or marketing messages that resonate with the characteristics of the target segments. For example, highlight the benefits of personal loans for higher-income individuals or those with larger families.
  • Cross-selling to CD Account Holders:
    • Actively promote personal loan options to customers who have CD accounts, as the model suggests they are more receptive to such offers. This can be done through online banking platforms, email campaigns, or even in-branch interactions.
  • Review of Current Strategies:
    • Re-evaluate existing personal loan marketing strategies to ensure they are aligned with the insights from the model. If current campaigns heavily rely on factors that the model shows are not important (like Age or Experience), consider shifting focus to the more influential attributes.

By implementing these recommendations, the bank can significantly improve the success rate of their personal loan campaigns by targeting the most promising segments of their liability customer base.
